04210nam a22006855i 9780691188263DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182002nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911882637 a10.1515/97806911882632doi  a(DE-B1597)501594  a(OCoLC)1076418542  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a291.909732231 aFaubion, James D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Shadows and Lights of Waco :bMillennialism Today /cJames D. Faubion. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aIn-Formation00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tProlegomena -- tPart One: A Conversion -- tPart Two: A Gnosis -- tPart Three: An Ethics -- tPart Four: A Colonization -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen James Faubion visited the site of the Branch Davidian compound after its conflagration, what he found surprised him. Though the popular imagination had relegated the site's millennialist denizens to the radical fringe, Faubion found not psychopathology but a sturdy and comprehensive system for understanding the world. He also found, in the person of Amo Paul Bishop Roden, a fascinating spokeswoman for that system. Based on more than five years of fieldwork, including extensive life-history interviews with Roden, Faubion interprets millennialism as a ''master-pedagogy.'' He reveals it as simultaneously a poetics, a rhetoric, a physics, an approach to history, a course of training, a gnosis, and an ethics. Millennialism resists the categories that both academic and popular analysts use to discuss religion by melding the sacred and secular, the spiritual and political, and the transcendental and commonsensical. In this respect, and in others, millennialism is a premodern pedagogy that has grown resolutely counter-modern. Yet, mainstream culture sees in it not a critique of modernity but dangerous lunacy. This disjunction prompts Faubion to investigate how the mainstream came to confine religion to an inner and other-worldly faith--an inquiry that allows him to account for the irrationalization of millennialism. Against this historical background, we can discern the genealogy of Adventist millennialism and make sense of contemporary religious events, including the actions of a small group in the central Texas prairie.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCultszUnited States. 0aWaco Branch Davidian Disaster, Tex., 1993. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188263zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691188263423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188263.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK